objects.name: WellLog.1.5.0
objects.description: A well log is a data type that correlates a particular measurement or multiple measurements in a wellbore against depth and/or time within that wellbore. When plotted visually, well logs are typically long line graphs (called "curves") but may sometimes be discrete points or intervals. This schema object is intended for digital well logs, not raster log files or raster calibration files, but may be used for the latter in the absence of a defined OSDU schema for these use cases.

objects.name: LogSource
objects.description: OSDU Native Log Source - will be updated for later releases - not to be used yet

objects.name: LogActivity
objects.description: Log Activity, used to describe the type of pass such as Calibration Pass - Main Pass - Repeated Pass

objects.name: LogRun
objects.description: Log Run - describe the run of the log - can be a number, but may be also a alphanumeric description such as a version name

objects.name: LogVersion
objects.description: Log Version

objects.name: LoggingService
objects.description: Logging Service - mainly a short concatenation of the names of the tools

objects.name: LogServiceDateInterval
objects.description: An interval built from two nested values : StartDate and EndDate. It applies to the whole log services and may apply to composite logs as [start of the first run job] and [end of the last run job]Log Service Date
objects.title: LogServiceDateInterval

objects.name: ToolStringDescription
objects.description: Tool String Description - a long concatenation of the tools used for logging services such as GammaRay+NeutronPorosity

objects.name: LoggingDirection
objects.description: Specifies whether curves were collected downward or upward

objects.name: PassNumber
objects.description: Indicates if the Pass is the Main one (1) or a repeated one - and it's level repetition

objects.name: ActivityType
objects.description: General method or circumstance of logging - MWD, completion, ...

objects.name: HoleTypeLogging
objects.description: Description of the hole related type of logging - POSSIBLE VALUE : OpenHole / CasedHole / CementedHole

objects.name: FrameIdentifier
objects.description: For multi-frame or multi-section files, this identifier defines the source frame in the file. If the identifier is an index number the index starts with zero and is converted to a string for this property.
objects.title: Frame Identifier

objects.name: SamplingInterval
objects.description: For regularly sampled curves this property holds the sampling interval. For non regular sampling rate this property is not set. The IsRegular flag indicates whether SamplingInterval is required.
objects.title: Sampling Interval

objects.name: ReferenceCurveID
objects.description: The data.Curves[].CurveID, which holds the primary index (reference) values.
objects.title: Reference Curve ID

objects.name: SamplingStart
objects.description: The start value/first value of the ReferenceCurveID, typically the start depth of the logging.
objects.title: Sampling Start

objects.name: SamplingStop
objects.description: The stop value/last value of the ReferenceCurveID, typically the end depth of the logging.
objects.title: Sampling Stop

objects.name: CandidateReferenceCurveIDs
objects.description: Secondary index curves, which are alternative candidates to act as ReferenceCurveID. Generally not populated, except in the cases where multiple reference curves are present, e.g. measured depth and time.

objects.name: ZeroTime
objects.description: Optional time reference for (calender) time logs. The ISO date time string representing zero time. Not to be confused with seismic travel time zero. The latter is defined by SeismicReferenceDatum.

objects.name: IsRegular
objects.description: Boolean property indicating the sampling mode of the ReferenceCurveID. True means all reference curve values are regularly spaced (see SamplingInterval); false means irregular or discrete sample spacing.
objects.title: Is Regular Flag

objects.name: LogRemark
objects.description: Log remark provides contextual information during the actual log object acquisition. Explains how the measurement in the wellbore is taken on a point in time or depth. Additional information may be included such as bad weather, tool failure, etc. Usually a part of the log header, log remark contains info specific for an acquisition run, specific for a given logging tool (multiple measurements) and/or a specific interval. In essence, log remark represents the external factors and operational environment, directly or indirectly affecting the measurement quality/uncertainty (dynamically over time/depth) - adding both noise and bias to the measurements.
objects.title: Log Remark

objects.name: CurveID
objects.description: The ID of the Well Log Curve

objects.name: DateStamp
objects.description: Date curve was created in the database

objects.name: CurveVersion
objects.description: The Version of the Log Curve.

objects.name: CurveQuality
objects.description: The Quality of the Log Curve.

objects.name: InterpreterName
objects.description: The name of person who interpreted this Log Curve.

objects.name: IsProcessed
objects.description: Indicates if the curve has been (pre)processed or if it is a raw recording

objects.name: NullValue
objects.description: Indicates that there is no measurement within the curve

objects.name: Interpolate
objects.description: Whether curve can be interpolated or not

objects.name: TopDepth
objects.description: The curve's minimum 'depth', i.e., the reference value at which the curve has its first non-absent value. The curve may contain further absent values in between TopDepth and BaseDepth. Note that the SamplingDomainType may not be a depth as the property name indicates.

objects.name: BaseDepth
objects.description: The curve's maximum 'depth' i.e., the reference value at which the curve has its last non-absent value. The curve may contain further absent values in between TopDepth and BaseDepth. Note that the SamplingDomainType may not be a depth as the property name indicates.

objects.name: Mnemonic
objects.description: The Mnemonic of the Log Curve is the value as received either from Raw Providers or from Internal Processing team

objects.name: NumberOfColumns
objects.description: The number of columns present in this Curve for a single reference value. For simple logs this is typically 1; for image logs this holds the number of image traces or property series. Further information about the columns can be obtained via the respective log or curve APIs of the Domain Data Management Service.
objects.title: Number Of Columns

objects.name: CurveDescription
objects.description: Mnemonic-level curve description is used during parsing or reading and ingesting LAS or DLIS files, to explain the type of measurement being looked at, specifically for that moment. Curve description is specific to that single (log) mnemonic and for the entire log (acquisition run) interval. In essence, curve description defines the internal factors such as what the "curve" or measurement ideally is representing, how is it calculated, what are the assumptions and the "constants".
objects.title: Curve Description
objects.example: CBL Adjustment Factor, Resistivity Inversion Selection, Detector 1 Barite Constant

relships.name: FlowingConditionID

relships.name: IndexTypeID

relships.name: PassTypeID
relships.description: The type of log pass such as Calibration Pass, Main Pass, Repeated Pass.

relships.name: LoggingDirectionID

The direction of logging for this log pass.
Specifies whether the logging information was collected in an downward or upward direction or stationary.

objectviews.name: WellLog.1.5.0
objectviews.description: A well log is a data type that correlates a particular measurement or multiple measurements in a wellbore against depth and/or time within that wellbore. When plotted visually, well logs are typically long line graphs (called "curves") but may sometimes be discrete points or intervals. This schema object is intended for digital well logs, not raster log files or raster calibration files, but may be used for the latter in the absence of a defined OSDU schema for these use cases.

relshipviews.description: The vertical measurement reference for this well logging acquisition activity. This object defines the vertical reference datum for the measured depths.

objecttypes.name: EntityType
objecttypes.description: An EntityType represents a category or class of similar entities in a data model, For example, a 'Customer' could be an EntityType with relationships to properties like name and address.aaaaaa

objecttypes.name: Value
objecttypes.description: Value represents the specific data assigned to a Property. It defines the actual content or figure, such as a numerical amount, text string, or boolean state, that the property holds.

objecttypes.name: ViewFormat
objecttypes.description: ViewFormat typically refers to a setting or attribute in software that determines how data or information is displayed or formatted in a user interface. It controls the visual presentation of data, such as layout, style, or format, enhancing readability and user experience.

objecttypes.name: InputPattern
objecttypes.description: InputPattern typically refers to a predefined format or rule that an input must follow. It's used to validate or guide user input, ensuring it matches a specific structure, like a date format or a phone number pattern. RegEx is typically used to specify the pattern.

objecttypes.name: Fieldtype
objecttypes.description: FieldType typically specify of the type of data contained in a field. (text, textarea, select, checkbox, radio, date, time, color)

objecttypes.name: Datatype
objecttypes.description: A datatype is a classification identifying the type of data, such as integer, string, or boolean, which determines the possible values for that type, the operations that can be performed on it, and the way it is stored.

objecttypes.name: Property
objecttypes.description: A property is an object representing an attribute of an entity that holds basic data, such as strings, numbers, or booleans. It defines specific characteristics of the entity, like 'name' or 'age'.

objecttypes.name: RelshipType
objecttypes.description: RelationshipType Object is used as a placeholder for relationship Properties. It will be generated as a relationship with  attributes.

objecttypes.name: Metamodel
objecttypes.description: Metamodel is a model that defines the Object and Relationship-types, rules and structures for creating other models. It provides a higher-level framework for understanding how different elements in a model relate and interact.

objecttypes.name: Method
objecttypes.description: Method is a function associated with an EntityType (object or class), defining an action or behavior the object can perform. It often manipulates the object's data properties and can return values.

objecttypes.name: MethodType
objecttypes.description: MethodType typically refers to an attribute that specifies the type or category of a method or function.
